The same-sex kiss in the Rise of Skywalker reminded me of how they handled a similar situation in 3 Below: Tales of Arcadia. During the Asteroid Rage episode, two girls say they never kissed anyone before, and so they kissed each other to compensate. It came out of nowhere and felt like pointless LGBT pandering.
What they could have done was set up that romance and have it interconnect to their main stories and have it actually contribute to their respective plots. That wuld have been a better way of handling it.

snippet.textDisplay: When you said alot of the things felt unplanned I think its because it was. I don't know this for sure, but from what i've heard JJ had no written road map for this, but he did have some sort of idea, and I think his idea can be seen in TFA. The issue is then Rian (or however he spells it) came in, and he did his own thing, that in many ways ruined what JJ was setting up. Episode 9 then turned into a massive retcon fest with a rushed villain that they had to pull from somewhere in the lore (Palpiten had clones in the EU its a whole thing you can look into), because JJs bad guy was killed off before he wanted him to be. The same basically goes for the other retcon elements such as Rays parents and Kylos mask. Overall I feel the problem comes from two people trying to tell two diffrent stories in the same trilogy. I honestly have no idea why JJ didn't make the last Jedi though.

Making this whole saga better:

Force Awakens:
- The Knights of Ren are epic
- Clone that escaped order 66 (similar to comics)

- Luke isn’t a BITCH
- Rey clearly becomes stronger due to Luke and actually trains. Luke could actually refer to Yoda’s training in some regard.

- I got bored carry on someone else please 😂😂😂

snippet.textDisplay: Personally, I quite enjoyed each of the movies. I thought they were funny, enjoyable, and quite fun to watch, given that I'm a huge Star Wars fan, to the point that A New Hope is my favourite movie, ever. With Rise of Skywalker, I don't think that it's just the end to this trilogy, I feel that's it the end to this whole nine film series, a trilogy of trilogies in a way. One thing I didn't quite like was that the Emperor returned, especially with such a little explanation as "Ugh, I don't know, clones." And then nothing, but I think it fits in with the rest of the Saga, considering it would make this feel more like an epilogue then a part of the series. Also, I genuinely don't like having Rey being related to the Emperor, given that I don't think she should be part of a lineage, cause she shouldn't need to be. Also I don't she can bring people back from the dead, I think that was just healing.

snippet.textDisplay:
Actually, the power to bring people back from the dead with the Force is established earlier in the Star Wars canon... as a forbidden power of the Dark Side of the Force, to the point where the Force itself said "this is going too far, I need to create a Chosen One specifically to counter this!"


Though to be fair, I'm pretty sure that both this and the Kingsmen example are technically cases of resuscitating dying characters, not resurrecting dead characters, so it doesn't really cheapen the death.

snippet.textDisplay:
This film... no this trilogy destroyed the prophecy of the chosen one... anakin who had been both in the light and in the dark side for an equal amount of time (more or less) ... and who in the end was able to change and bring (should have been an eternal) peace to the galaxy (like the prophecy said) thanks to his son Luke (u could consider them both to be the chosen one) but this movie (rise of skyWalker) destroyed the prophecy and showed that all the effort that the characters put in those movie was just a temporary thing so that this girl could save the galaxy defeating palpatine in 2 seconds ... a purpose for which Vader had to sacrifice his life.
I am not saying that this movie was shitty (after seeing the last Jedi... u could say I am “happy” with what they were able to save of the franchise) but it was surely mediocre ... they could have brought more actors (ghosts force) for this movie instead of just using their voices (which was a good idea) ... making anakin have a role in restoring the balance and defeating palpatine and bringing back the Jedi of the precedent films (but living the final strike to Rey as symbol of the new generation arise)... instead they just made a shitty final fight (if u want to call it a fight) between Rey and palpatine (kylo hadn’t any role in the last film... like his only job was to bring Rey back to life by using the force... a thing that not even anakin was able to do... (for which he decided to become palpatine apprentice) and wasn’t done by almost anyone but just speculated and to do this u should have trained and studied a lot about the unnatural powers of the dark side ...but this trilogy motto is fuck the training we have plot armor (tell that to Luke and anakin arm))
You can say whatever u want about the prequels they have their flaws but at least they were congruent about the main points of the narrative instead the sequels... they can have really nice dialogues/humour and acting but the story and the narrative is all fucked up (Leia waking up and flying in the space... Luke’s “light side” that was able to bring back Vader (a sociopathic mass murderer) from the dark side ... how the fuck did he give up on his nephew (and don’t tell me that it was a moment of weakness because even mark hamill said that it was bullshit... like every person that did the original trilogy and was in these movies said that they were shitty ))
They could have done so much more to end the franchise in a great way but they ended up creating a basic plot which was for the most part a copy of the original trilogy... they didn’t even come close to making a film that ended an era (which was 50 years long) as endgame which was a great/magnificent conclusion for the firsts avengers
